The paper deals with hypergraph partitioning, which is a problem in graph theory and computer science. The most likely category is cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) as the paper proposes a new algorithm for hypergraph partitioning. The second likely category is cs.SI (Social and Information Networks) as the paper mentions social networks as an example of applications that can be modeled as hypergraphs. The third likely category is cs.DM (Discrete Mathematics) as hypergraph theory is a subfield of discrete mathematics. The fourth likely category is cs.CE (Computational Engineering, Finance, and Science) as hypergraph partitioning is relevant to many real-world applications. The fifth likely category is cs.DB (Databases) as the paper mentions distributed databases as an example of applications that can be modeled as hypergraphs.
